    // 1. gcd(S) = p
    // 2. |S| < n

    // Case 1: Subsequence of length 1.
    // If there exists any element nums[i] = p, then {nums[i]} is a good subsequence (since n >= 2, 1 < n).
    if (nums.includes(p)) {
        return true;
    }

    // Case 2: Subsequence of length >= 2.
    // If we can find any pair (nums[i], nums[j]) with i != j such that gcd(nums[i], nums[j]) = p,
    // then {nums[i], nums[j]} is a good subsequence (since n >= 2, 2 <= n-1 is true for n >= 3. If n=2, 2 is not < 2.
    // Wait, if n=2, the only non-empty subsequences are {n1}, {n2}, {n1, n2}.
    // If n=2, |S| < 2 means |S| = 1. So if n=2, we only need Case 1.

    if (n === 2) {
        // If n=2, |S| must be 1. We already checked this (nums.includes(p)).
        return false;
    }

